To every woman working 2 jobs just to keep the lights on. Went hungry so their kids can eat. Who said, "I'm sorry we can't. But I promise one day we will."...
Remember why you started.
To every woman who was scared to jump but took the risk and failed 10 times just to hit rock bottom....
Remember why you started.
To every woman holding themselves together everyday even when they can't get out of bed....
Remember why you started.
To every woman, who's world tries to convince them over and over again to "sit down and shut up."..

REMEMBER WHY YOU F'N STARTED!
Because…. once upon a time, you were a little girl with big dreams in your heart. And YOU promised her you'd make them come true... And you will.

Caution angry post.
After 16 years in my business
Chaps, today may have been my most challenging. Ive had difficult days in the past- we struggled today. While kitchens can be dysfunctional workplaces I pride myself on the culture of Chaps. I love, admire, & respect my staff.
This is my non-negotiable manifesto- food is love. I hope we extend this to you- the community I foster. I have a 19-year-old chef, hardworking, committed, and naive.
His father committed suicide
yesterday. Against all our trying, he insisted on coming to work today, where he felt the most embraced & loved. It slowed us down, we were worried about him, we lost focus & the ability to stay on point. But he was here with us, surrounded by support & love, & I could not talk him out of it.This industry must develop new role models & practice that promotes healthier work environments. Our service was slow, at one point a customer was so mad- we shared with them the situation they replied I don't care! demanding the return of a tip and reimbursement of the meal. If you were here today and we weren't perfect I sincerely apologize. Albeit, I want to share this; if you come here behave. The customer isn't always right, please don't get in my line if you want to be demanding, insulting, or rude. Write as many bad reviews as you like, but five gold stars to my amazing supportive crew today who held another human being together. Even as the pandemic upends the restaurant world, this reform can & must happen. Diners are now, finally, accustomed to thinking about, if not always respecting, the health and well-being of industry employees, who bear frontline risks as restaurants reopen. Ultimately, restaurants are as much about people as they are about food.
That's newly in focus these days when so many industry employees are hurting. None of us, whether we're in the restaurant as diners, reporters, critics, or workers, should go on centering food at the expense of those who prepare and serve it.
It's well past time to treat restaurant labor with the same consideration given to ingredients. These workers have too often felt like they have no choice but to accept abysmal treatment.

We had a plan for a new little shop to open on September 23, 23. However with a moratorium in our Vinegar Flats neighborhood we had to pause. Why Sept 23….On this day in 2020 (if you know me you remember) I nearly lost my precious Meg and my little granddaughter. Megan had a severe placenta percreta. She had a massive hemorrhage while pregnant and during an emergency premature delivery – slipped away quickly. We had all fallen to our knees. The very memory pierces my soul. Yet Meg holds a secret only belonging to her & God. A 4lb Collette Renee took her own quick breath & God whispered to Meg-“stay”. This is my love letter to God, Coco , and you Meg. “dear coco,……..” 
Opening soon ( sooner than we had planned) in downtown Spokane, . For the community I love. Café Coco July 2023 
( Ps today mom and Baby are perfect and healthy)❤️
